.Dd 2026-07-20
.Dt AUDIOCTL 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm audioctl
.Nd uniform control of the default audio output and input
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Ar command
.Op Ar arg
.Nm
.Op Fl h | Fl -help | Cm help
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
provides a single subcommand interface to the default audio output
(speakers) and input (microphone), independent of the underlying system.
On
.Ox
it drives
.Xr sndioctl 1 ;
on Linux it drives
.Xr wpctl 1
against the
.Qq @DEFAULT_SINK@
and
.Qq @DEFAULT_SOURCE@
nodes.
.Pp
Volumes are reported and accepted as a linear fraction in the range
.Sq 0.0
to
.Sq 1.0 .
Mute state is reported as
.Sq 1
(muted) or
.Sq 0
(unmuted).
.Sh COMMANDS
.Bl -tag -width "set-mic-volume Ar volume" -compact
.It Ic get-volume
Print the output volume.
.It Ic set-volume Ar volume
Set the output volume.
.It Ic is-muted
Print
.Sq 1
if the output is muted,
.Sq 0
otherwise.
.It Ic set-muted Ar 0 Ns | Ns Ar 1
Mute or unmute the output.
.It Ic get-mic-volume
Print the microphone volume.
.It Ic set-mic-volume Ar volume
Set the microphone volume.
.It Ic is-mic-muted
Print
.Sq 1
if the microphone is muted,
.Sq 0
otherwise.
.It Ic set-mic-muted Ar 0 Ns | Ns Ar 1
Mute or unmute the microphone.
.El
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl h , -help , Cm help
Print the usage and exit.
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Sh EXAMPLES
Set the output volume to 50%:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ audioctl set-volume 0.5
.Ed
.Pp
Mute the microphone:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ audioctl set-mic-muted 1
.Ed
.Pp
Poll the microphone mute state (this is the call made by
.Xr bedstatus 1 Ns 's
microphone indicator):
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ audioctl is-mic-muted
0
.Ed
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr sndioctl 1 ,
.Xr wpctl 1 ,
.Xr bedstatus 1
.Sh BUGS
.Ox
already ships a system
.Xr audioctl 8
with the same name; installing this script to
.Pa /usr/local/bin/audioctl
shadows it on
.Ev PATH .
.Pp
FreeBSD is not handled by the per-OS dispatch; the subcommands silently
no-op there.
